00:11:20.000 --> 00:11:29.000
People see it. I never know sometimes, like, sending something out ahead of a meeting, are people actually even going to go through it, or do you assume that they will?

00:11:31.000 --> 00:11:41.000
I would say yes, ahead of time, but usually, I feel like the kind of, you know, slides that you get for the presentation, that's usually in the meeting.

00:11:41.000 --> 00:11:51.000
I would say yes, ahead of time, but usually, I feel like the kind of, you know, slides that you get for the presentation, that's usually in the meeting, but usually, I feel like the kind of.

00:11:51.000 --> 00:12:00.000
Storytelling streamline talk that like you would do at this conference is very different from the kind of slide decks, I tend to send out at work, or that gets sent around at work, the ones that work.

00:12:00.000 --> 00:12:11.000
They're information dense, they have a lot of numbers, a lot of tables, a lot of charts, like, you're intending to spend time with it and read it and stare at the numbers and understand the report out of the results of the test or whatever.

00:12:11.000 --> 00:12:19.000
Which is very different than this sort of talk, where I think, like, the deposit talk, where they're encouraging us to have minimal stuff on the screen and people should listen to our words. Right?

00:12:19.000 --> 00:12:25.000
So, I think it's super important for, like, information dense decks that are kind of half.

00:12:25.000 --> 00:12:33.000
A document to be read and half to be talked through and as opposed to, like, this sort of conference where I think the decks will be.

00:12:33.000 --> 00:12:43.000
Considerably less information does, I guess I'm trying to also figure out what's the difference then and presenting a story.

00:12:43.000 --> 00:12:50.000
To people in a conference and getting them to understand what you're saying versus, like, getting your colleagues to understand.

00:12:50.000 --> 00:13:07.000
The key story behind the data too. Yeah, I've been thinking about that because, like, I kind of wonder how useful, like, we have an internal conference here for analysts and I kind of was telling some folks, you know, maybe something like articulation ink coming to us before the next internal conference would be good.

