00:54:26.000 --> 00:54:39.000
I wanted to circle back for a second to George's question before, because Alan, I see you shared some other thoughts in the chat. Is it OK if I kind of pull you in here to share that?

00:54:40.000 --> 00:55:00.000
Yeah, I think my thoughts were sort of regardless of the sort of like rollout method, the way you make that kind of data available, I think being sort of a facilitator or enabler kind of as long as it takes is really important so that you set up really clear expectations about like, what is this data good for?

00:55:01.000 --> 00:55:12.000
What does it support well versus what does it not support well? And that way you can sort of be riding along helping people think about like, in your case, compliance issues or those kinds of things in particular.

00:55:13.000 --> 00:55:24.000
And it's a whole lot easier. And we found this over the course of trying to sort of course correct some big long kind of multi-year projects. It's a whole lot easier to do that at the beginning than later.

00:55:24.000 --> 00:55:36.000
So it's really exciting to roll stuff out. And also, it's really, really helpful and important to sort of like everybody look around the table and you go, OK, wait, let's do this slowly. Let's do this really carefully.

00:55:37.000 --> 00:55:49.000
But it's a real balance of like feeling success on the part of your team and your mission and setting up your stakeholders for longer term kind of success and stability and stuff.

